      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gas Taxes Curb Pollution</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Irisita Azary letter says replacing gasoline as auto fuel with ethanol would mean more pollution and a higher total consumption of oil; notes that ethanol cannot be produced without expenditure of a significant amount of gasoline (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You periodically mention ethanol as an alternative to gasoline, as in your Nov. 30 front-page article on light trucks. However, many studies have shown that it takes more petroleum to grow the corn and process it into ethanol than the ethanol replaces when it is burned.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You periodically mention ethanol as an alternative to gasoline, as in your Nov. 30 front-page article on light trucks. However, many studies have shown that it takes more petroleum to grow the corn and process it into ethanol than the ethanol replaces when it is burned.</p>
        <p>Thus, burning ethanol increases both our dependence on petroleum and emissions of carbon dioxide and air pollutants. The promotion of ethanol, as you correctly state, is primarily a way of providing a market for corn. Moreover, Federal subsidies for ethanol are primarily a subsidy of Archer Daniels Midland, which controls most of the ethanol market.</p>
        <p>IRISITA  AZARY</p>
        <p>Long Beach, Calif., Dec. 1, 1997</p>
        <p>The writer is an assistant professor of geography, California State U.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
